\section*{Dimensions and Units}

We note that when we take the scalar part of a vector perturbation the
dimension of the quantity changes by one length factor (L) i.e.
\be
\left[V\right] = L \left[{V_i}\right]  \,.
\ee
We also not that when moving to Fourier space quantities will have
three extra length dimension units, i.e.
\be
\left[V (k) \right] = L^3 \left[{V}(x) \right]  \,.
\ee
Finally we list some of the quantities we work with and their dimensions,
where L represents a length dimension, m, a mass dimension, t a time dimension and B a magnetic dimension,
such as Tesla or Gauss. Note that the magnetic units are related to the charge units by,
$T = kg C^{-1} s^{-1}$.
